caption: BEST SUSHI EVER! I have eaten a lot of sushi over my sixty years...this was by far the best ever. So fresh...so tasty. Excellent service. Great atmosphere. I had a Dancing Dragon Roll, nigri Hamachi, a ginger salad and a Kirin beer. Prices were reasonable and it was worth every penny. Two thumbs up. Give it a try!

I've been coming here since they opened, so I can't believe I haven't reviewed them until now!  Pre-COVID, I probably came here at least once a month, but this time around, I've been ordering on Uber Eats.  Starting with the Vegetable Spring Rolls, they were okay.  They didn't have much flavor to them and were a bit soggy on the inside.  They were alright, but not my favorite.  The Zukku Roll was pretty good.  There's A LOT going on with it, but between the sweet and savoriness of the eel sauce and spicy mayo on top, it worked really well.  It is a bit messy to eat, but I really enjoyed it.  The Godzilla Burrito was good as well, but not the best we've had from them.  The first burrito we had was their Flamin' Hot Cheeto burrito and I wish they'd bring that back as a full-time menu item.  There's just something about the balance between the crunchy, sweet inside of a sushi burrito with the spiciness and crunch of the Cheeto that we can't seem to get from their other burritos like that one.  Maybe we need to try some more customization to them.  Overall, I can't wait to go back and enjoy their food in the comfort of Armature Works and enjoy the hustle and bustle of everyone anxiously waiting in line for their food.  It's always a popular spot and their food echoes why.

Great spot for sushi! This place is located inside the Armature works building. I stopped by on a late Friday evening looking for a quick bite. The menu has several options to select from such as a sushi bowl or a sushi burrito however you can also choose to create your own. I had a poke bowl with tuna and salmon served over some greens and rice. My significant other had a sushi burrito with shrimp tempura. To drink we went with a Sapporo beer and the milk boba thai tea. Everything was fresh and delicious.  There was a bit of a line while ordering however they have a pretty good system down. Once you place your order you are given one of those light up pagers that let you know when your food is ready and someone is there ensuring you pick up the correct order. It was pretty busy when we were there but located a place to sit that was close by. This is definitely a place to check out if you like sushi. I'll definitely be back to check out other items they have!

I'm all about clean eating and poke is such a go to for me as a replacement for sushi. I love things that are low carb and high protein - leaving me with a fresh and light meal. This is just that.  I'm giving only 3/5 starts here today because this poke is EXPENSIVE for what it is. The brown rice is extra, the meats are limited in portion (very few raw options, most are cooked), and then only 3 toppings. I usually like to load up my poke bowls with lots of veg and toppings in order to supplement the poke and make it more of a salad bowl.  However, I did like the roasted mango topping that I got, and the fact that the tuna was fresh (I got raw tuna and salmon). The ordering is pretty streamline as well because you just mark what you want on a laminated menu, and hand it to the cashier.  They hand you a buzzer/pager when you pay because they take a while to prepare it even though its just down the buffet line to assemble. I'm not sure why they do that.  Probably would choose to explore another option at this food venue.

Tuna is not fresh. My husband got very sick after eating here back in February and missed a day of work. I called Zukku to alert them that their tuna was bad. The manager on duty said the owner would send me a gift card to compensate for the bad experience. I never received a gift card. If they had sent it, I would use it for a vegan dish and NOT the raw fish. Be careful here.

I’ve always enjoyed Zukku for poke bowls except for my visit today. I ordered a poke bowl with salmon and tuna, and, unfortunately, the tuna was not fresh. It was discolored, smelled, and tasted fishy.  I took the uneaten tuna back to the restaurant and very nicely explained that I’ve enjoyed Zukku many times before but that today the tuna was too old to eat and that they probably shouldn’t serve it to anyone else. One of the chefs asked if he could try a bite. When he did, he agreed that it was not fresh. I expected that, at that point, they might offer me a substitute fish or even a refund, but they did neither. They simply returned to work on preparing food. I’m not sure whether they actually disposed of the remaining tuna or not, but I was very disappointed in how they managed (or didn’t manage as the case may be) the issue. What could have easily have been addressed was not, and I will be reluctant to eat there in the future, which is a real disappointment.
